model_explanation: “only … ELLEN … grapes” means Ellen was the sole recipient of grapes, so Tom did not get grapes.
“only … APPLES” means Ellen received no items other than apples, so not oranges.
“only … GRAPES” limits what Rob received (only grapes) but doesn’t restrict who else got grapes; Ellen may also have received grapes.
the restriction is only on what Rob received (only apples), not on whether others (like Ellen) also got apples.
limiting Ellen’s items to apples says nothing about whether Bill received apples.
limiting Rob’s items to apples says nothing about whether Sue received apples.
“only … ROB … oranges” means Rob was the sole recipient of oranges; it doesn’t forbid also giving Rob apples.
“only … ROB … apples” means Rob was the sole recipient of apples; it doesn’t forbid also giving Rob grapes.
